To create a C program using WiringPi to control an LED connected to GPIO pin 17 (BCM GPIO 17), you'll first need to install WiringPi. If you haven't done so, follow the installation instructions provided in the official WiringPi GitHub repository: https://github.com/WiringPi/WiringPi

Once WiringPi is installed, create a new file named `led_button.c` and paste the following code:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <wiringPi.h>

#define LED_PIN 17
#define BUTTON_PIN 27
#define DELAY 100

int main() {
    wiringPiSetupGpio();

    // Set the LED pin as output and the button pin as input
    pinMode(LED_PIN, OUTPUT);
    pullUpDnControl(BUTTON_PIN, PUD_UP);
    pinMode(BUTTON_PIN, INPUT);

    int state = 0;

    while (1) {
        if (digitalRead(BUTTON_PIN) == LOW) {
            // Button is pressed, toggle LED state
            state = !state;
            digitalWrite(LED_PIN, state);
        }

        usleep(DELAY * 1000); // Delay for debouncing
    }

    return 0;
}
```

Save the file and compile it using the following command:

```
gcc led_button.c -o led_button -lwiringPi
```

After compiling, run the program with the following command:

```
sudo ./led_button
```

Now, connect the LED anode to GPIO pin 17 (BCM GPIO 17) and the cathode to ground. Connect the button between GPIO pin 27 (BCM GPIO 27) and ground. When you press the button, the LED should turn on and off when released.

