To create a C program for Raspberry Pi Zero W that triggers a buzzer connected to GPIO 18 upon detecting motion from an HC-SR501 PIR sensor connected to GPIO 17, using the `pigpio` library and syslog for logging events, follow these steps:

1. First, make sure you have the `wiringPi` and `pigpio` libraries installed on your Raspberry Pi. If not, you can install them using the following commands:

```bash
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install wiringPi
sudo pigpio --update
sudo apt-get install pigpio
```

2. Create a new file called `pir_buzzer.c` and paste the following code into it:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <syslog.h>
#include <time.h>
#include <wiringPi.h>
#include <pigpio.h>

#define PIR_PIN 17
#define BUZZER_PIN 18
#define DELAY_MS 1000

void log_event(const char *event) {
    openlog("pir_buzzer", LOG_PID | LOG_CONS | LOG_PERROR, LOG_USER);
    syslog(LOG_INFO, "%s: %s at %s", getenv("USER"), event, ctime(&time(NULL)));
    closelog();
}

void init_gpio() {
    if (wiringPiSetupGpio() == -1) {
        log_event("Failed to initialize wiringPi");
        exit(1);
    }

    if (gpioInitialise() < 0) {
        log_event("Failed to initialize pigpio");
        exit(1);
    }

    pinMode(PIR_PIN, INPUT);
    pullUpDnControl(PIR_PIN, PUD_UP);
    pinMode(BUZZER_PIN, OUTPUT);
    digitalWrite(BUZZER_PIN, LOW);
}

int main() {
    init_gpio();

    int state = 0;
    while (1) {
        if (digitalRead(PIR_PIN) == HIGH && state == 0) {
            log_event("Motion detected");
            digitalWrite(BUZZER_PIN, HIGH);
            state = 1;
        } else if (digitalRead(PIR_PIN) == LOW && state == 1) {
            log_event("Motion ended");
            digitalWrite(BUZZER_PIN, LOW);
            state = 0;
            sleep(DELAY_MS / 1000.0);
        }
    }

    gpioTerminate();
    return 0;
}
```

3. Compile the code using gcc:

```bash
gcc -o pir_buzzer pir_buzzer.c -lwiringPi -lpthread -lpigpio
```

4. Run the compiled program with sudo:

```bash
sudo ./pir_buzzer
```

This program initializes the GPIO pins using both `wiringPi` and `pigpio` libraries, sets up the PIR sensor on GPIO 17 as an input with a pull-up resistor, and the buzzer on GPIO 18 as an output. It then enters an infinite loop where it checks the state of the PIR sensor and triggers the buzzer when motion is detected.

In case of any errors during initialization, the program logs the error message to syslog and exits. The program also logs motion detection and motion ended events to syslog.

