Here's a C program for Raspberry Pi 3 Model B+ that uses the `wiringPi` library to detect motion using an HC-SR501 PIR sensor connected to GPIO 17, logs timestamped activation events to a file named `security_log.txt`, and implements robust error handling for GPIO initialization failures.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <time.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <wiringPi.h>

#define PIR_PIN 17
#define LOG_FILE "security_log.txt"

void log_event(const char *message) {
    FILE *log_file = fopen(LOG_FILE, "a");
    if (log_file == NULL) {
        perror("Error opening log file");
        return;
    }

    time_t now = time(NULL);
    char timestamp[20];
    strftime(timestamp, sizeof(timestamp), "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S", localtime(&now));
    fprintf(log_file, "%s: %s\n", timestamp, message);
    fclose(log_file);
}

int main(void) {
    if (wiringPiSetupGpio() == -1) {
        perror("Error initializing wiringPi");
        return 1;
    }

    pinMode(PIR_PIN, INPUT);
    pullUpDnControl(PIR_PIN, PUD_UP);

    while (1) {
        if (digitalRead(PIR_PIN) == LOW) {
            log_event("Motion detected");
        }
        sleep(1);
    }

    return 0;
}
```

Before running the program, make sure you have the `wiringPi` library installed on your Raspberry Pi:

```
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install wiringPi
```

Compile and run the program:

```
gcc -o motion_detector motion_detector.c -lwiringPi -o motion_detector
sudo ./motion_detector
```

This program will run indefinitely, checking the PIR sensor's state every second and logging motion events to the `security_log.txt` file. If there is an error during GPIO initialization or opening the log file, it will print an error message and exit the program.

